            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#JP">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name>Ἰάσων</name></persName> <roleName type="paracivic.religious" subtype="presbyter">πρεσβύτε
                    <lb n="2" break="no"/>ρος</roleName> μηδὲν ζημι
                    <lb n="3" break="no"/>ώσας τὴν ἐντολ
                    <lb n="4" break="no"/>ήν ἠγόρασεν ἑαυ
                    <lb n="5" break="no"/>τῷ καὶ τοῖ<supplied reason="omitted">ς</supplied> τέκν
                    <lb n="6" break="no"/>οις ἑαυτοῦ τὴ
                    <lb n="7" break="no"/>ν κοῦπαν ταύτ
                    <lb n="8" break="no"/>ην
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text from autopsy</note></app>
                    <app loc="2"><note>The form of the final Μ is curious/heavily compressed, but also obscured by the modern repainting.</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>Jason the Elder, in no way infringing the law, bought for himself and his children this burial
                    place.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#SA">
                <p>Jason il presbitero, non violando la legge in alcun modo, ha acquistato per sé e per i suoi figli
                    questo luogo di sepoltura.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Jason is a common Jewish name. Presbyter simply means ‘elder’, but in this context signifies
                    membership of a council of elders. It is not certain that this text is Jewish, but the word entole
                    is a distinctively Jewish term in epitaphs, signifying the Mosaic law. The word koupa is very rare
                    in Greek (two out of three other instances also from Catania), transliterating the Latin cupa, which
                    generally describes a tomb in the shape of a half-barrel (cut lengthways). It is common to record
                    the purchase of the burial space in this way.</p>
            </div>
